an, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Chetwynd","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Chatwin  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Chatwin","meanings":["English (Warwickshire and Staffordshire): habitational name from a place in Shropshire called Chetwynd, from the Old English personal name <i>Ceatta</i> + Old English <i>(ge)wind</i> ‘winding ascent’."]}]},{"name":"Adam","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Hebrew: The Scripture name, in Hebrew, Adham, signifying 'man;' literally earthy, red earth; Rudolph, however, says the name in Ethiopic means ' to be fair, beautiful.' Hence the nurse-name Addy, little Adam."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Adam de Chetwynd was born about 1158, in Chetwynd, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom as the son of John I de Chetwynd. He married Agnes de Lovel in 1194, in Chetwynd, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. He died in 1210, at the age of 53."},"et":{"about 1158–1210":"umbes 1158–1210","1158–1210":"1158–1210","–Male":"Surnud","1193–1286":"1193–1286","1210–1318":"1210–1318","1188–1240":"1188–1240","1207–Male":"1207–Surnud","1209–1240":"1209–1240","1211–Male":"1211–Surnud","1132–Male":"1132–Surnud","1132":"1132","1286":"1286","1240":"1240","1194":"1194","1193":"1193","1158":"1158","about 1207":"umbes 1207","Abt 1188":"umbes 1188","1211":"1211","abt 1209":"umbes 1209","1210":"1210","1188":"1188","about 1158":"umbes 1158","about 1210":"umbes 1210","1209":"1209","1318":"1318","1207":"1207","Chetwynd, Shropshire, England, United Kingdom":"Chetwynd, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Chetwynd, Shrops., Eng.":"Chetwynd, Shropshire, Inglismaa, United